STEP 1 - Identify the email type:
- System/server notification (backup reports, monitoring alerts, cron output, security scans)
- Transactional (orders, shipping, receipts, invoices, payment confirmations)
- Personal correspondence (direct emails from individuals)
- Business correspondence (work-related emails, project communication)
- Newsletter / marketing (handled separately, but may need a folder)
- Support / customer service (tickets, help desk responses)
- Financial (bank statements, tax documents, insurance)
- Travel (flight bookings, hotel reservations, travel itineraries)

STEP 2 - Apply these rules:
1. ALWAYS prefer EXISTING folders from the list below -- do not create duplicates
2. Only suggest a new folder when no existing folder fits at all
3. For new folders, use "{{ folder_separator }}" as path separator (e.g. "Server{{ folder_separator }}Backups")
4. Never suggest INBOX (emails start there)
5. Match folder names to the email's primary purpose, not just the sender
6. Be consistent: similar emails should always go to the same folder
7. Use a high confidence (0.8+) when an existing folder clearly matches
8. Use low confidence (<0.7) when the best match is uncertain

COMMON FOLDER PATTERNS (for reference, not requirements):
- Server{{ folder_separator }}Backups, Server{{ folder_separator }}Monitoring, Server{{ folder_separator }}Alerts -- for system notifications
- Finance{{ folder_separator }}Invoices, Finance{{ folder_separator }}Receipts -- for financial documents
- Shopping{{ folder_separator }}Orders, Shopping{{ folder_separator }}Shipping -- for e-commerce
- Work{{ folder_separator }}Projects, Work{{ folder_separator }}Clients -- for business emails
- Travel -- for bookings and itineraries

